THE government has rehabilitated more than 2,000 kilometers of roads in national parks and other protected areas, courtesy of Covid-19 funds, the Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Tourism and Natural Resources, Dr Francis Michael has said. Dr Michael who was speaking shortly before donating safety and hygienic equipment to operators in tourism and hospitality industry here at the weekend said the government had also rehabilitated eight airstrips located in different national parks in the country to improve connectivity for both domestic and international travellers. He said the government focused on rehabilitation of the infrastructure in readiness of expected influx of tourists as tourism sector is recovering from negative impacts of Covid-19 pandemic. “We need to be ready in terms of infrastructure and matters of health as well, mindful that the pandemic is still around,” said the Permanent Secretary. In coping with the projected influx, Dr Michael further revealed that the government will be establishing new 14 national park gates in various destinations. “We’ve, on a number of occasions, experienced a fleet of 300 safari vehicles trying to access one destination at a go, we thought it was also important to add the number of entry points,” he said. Dr Michael assured tour operators in Tanzania that the government was planning to establish a Ministerial portal that will enable tourism related services easily. The Permanent Secretary further disclosed that IT experts at the Ministry were working round the clock, to ensure that a single window system becomes up and running soon. A total of 140,000 masks and 14, 285 sanitisers were handed to 10 local operators during the event.